## How It Works

HTTP PUT is defined as a full replacement operation in RFC 7231. The server replaces the entire resource at the target URL with the representation sent in the request body. If the client omits fields, those fields are overwritten with whatever defaults the server applies — typically null or empty values.

HTTP PATCH (RFC 5789) applies a partial modification. The server interprets the request body as a set of changes to merge into the current state. With JSON Merge Patch (RFC 7396), only the fields present in the request body are modified; all other fields remain unchanged.

PUT is idempotent because sending the same full representation repeatedly results in the same state. PATCH is not inherently idempotent — applying "increment counter by 1" twice produces a different result than applying it once.

## Code Example

```javascript
let user = { name: "Alice", email: "alice@old.com", phone: "555-0100" }

function handlePut(body) {
  // PUT replaces everything
  Object.assign(user, body)
}

function handlePatch(changes) {
  // PATCH merges only changed fields
  Object.assign(user, changes)
}

// Client sends PUT with email-only body
handlePut({ email: "alice@new.com" })
// Result: { email: "alice@new.com" }
// name and phone are gone — silent data loss

user = { name: "Alice", email: "alice@old.com", phone: "555-0100" }

// Client sends PATCH with the same body
handlePatch({ email: "alice@new.com" })
// Result: { name: "Alice", email: "alice@new.com", phone: "555-0100" }
// All fields preserved
```

## Key Points

- **PUT is full replacement**: every field not in the body is lost
- **PATCH is partial update**: only specified fields are modified
- **Idempotency**: PUT is idempotent, PATCH is not
- **Retry safety**: PUT can be retried automatically; PATCH may need idempotency keys
- **No error on data loss**: the server reports 200 OK — the client gets no warning

## Common Mistake

Treating PUT like a "partial update" operation. Developers routinely send incomplete request bodies to PUT expecting the server to merge changes into the existing resource. No error is returned, so the data loss goes unnoticed until a user reports missing fields. The root cause is conceptual: in REST, PUT means "set the resource to this exact state," not "update these fields."

## Interview Tip

The interviewer is testing whether you understand REST method semantics at the specification level, not just memorized definitions. A strong answer explains the idempotency property as the reason for PUT's design: full replacement guarantees idempotency. A great answer also mentions that the fix depends on context — PATCH for partial client-driven updates, or full-resource PUT when the client has the complete state and wants safe retries (e.g., idempotent payments).
